{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487278"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/307"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.16,0.38,0.24,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11063"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painful swelling in her left breast. She is otherwise well, with no previous breast problems and no family history of breast disease. She does not take any regular medications. She reports that the lump is tender when she presses on it or wears certain bras, and is also concerned as her friend was recently diagnosed with breast cancer. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no erythematous changes in the breast and no evidence of nipple changes. There is a mildy-tender, smooth-surfaced lump in the upper, outer quadrant of the left breast. An ultrasound confirms the presence of a 15 mm simple, thin-walled cyst and a mammogram shows BIRADS B density without any concerning lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical excision","Repeat ultrasound in three months","Fine needle aspiration","Reassurance and no follow-up","Repeat ultrasound in six months"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a simple, thin-walled breast cyst confirmed on ultrasound, which is a common benign finding in people in this age group. The cyst is causing her some discomfort and anxiety, particularly given her friend\u0027s recent cancer diagnosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for symptomatic or anxiety-provoking simple cysts, as it can relieve symptoms and provide reassurance. Aspiration is a minimally invasive procedure and does not increase the risk of complications when performed for simple cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and no follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is suitable for asymptomatic simple cysts in people at average risk, but in this case, the patient\u0027s anxiety and mild tenderness make aspiration a reasonable next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for a simple cyst without suspicious features or failed aspiration. Surgical removal is reserved for cysts with atypical features, solid components, or those that recur and remain symptomatic after aspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in three months\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat ultrasound in six months\u003C/strong\u003E are not necessary for a simple, thin-walled cyst without suspicious features. Serial imaging is reserved for indeterminate or complex cysts, or if there is a change in clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimple breast cysts are common and benign. Management is guided by symptoms and patient preference. Most resolve spontaneously, and the risk of malignancy is extremely low when classic features are present on imaging. Fine needle aspiration is safe and effective for symptomatic or anxiety-provoking cysts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Simple breast cysts confirmed on imaging and causing symptoms or patient anxiety can be managed with fine needle aspiration.","Reassurance without follow-up is appropriate for asymptomatic simple cysts in people at average risk.","Routine excision or serial imaging is not indicated for simple, thin-walled breast cysts without suspicious features."],"references":["Rao R, Ludwig K, Bailey L, et al. Select Choices in Benign Breast Disease: An Initiative of the American Society of Breast Surgeons for the American Board of Internal Medicine Choosing Wisely\u00a0Campaign. Ann Surg Oncol. 2018. 25:2795-800. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29968026/","Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions. Australian Family Physician. 2005. 34:253-55. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/f4b622a6-2af1-46b0-b51d-df52c58ccef2/attachment.aspx","Cancer Australia. The investigation of a new breast symptom - a guide for General Practitioners. 2021. Available at: https://cancerwa.asn.au/assets/public/2022/07/2022-03-23-investigation-of-a-new-breast-symptom-a-guide-for-general-practitioners.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T16:31:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T16:35:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"}